[m[38:2:248:248:242m●[39m Fair confusion. Here's the real reason — it's an apples/oranges thing:

[m  [22;1mA[22m [22;1mgame[22m [22;1mand[22m [22;1ma[22m [22;1mUI[22m [22;1mtoolkit[22m [22;1mrender[22m [22;1mcompletely[22m [22;1mdifferently.

[m  - [22;1mA[22m [22;1mgame[22m = one tight loop you wrote, pushing big batched draw calls straight to the GPU.
[m  The CPU barely touches individual objects. The GPU does the heavy lifting and it's idle
[m  99% of the time on your 3070 Ti. Drawing 1400 textured quads? Nothing. <1ms.
[m  - [22;1mA[22m [22;1mUI[22m [22;1mtoolkit[22m [22;1m(Avalonia)[22m = "retained mode." Every card is a tree of ~13 managed C#
[m  objects (Border, Panel, Grid, Button, Image...). Every frame you scroll, the framework
[m  walks ~1400 of those objects [22;1mon[22m [22;1mone[22m [22;1mCPU[22m [22;1mthread[22m — measure, arrange, diff, serialize to the
[m  compositor. That CPU walk is the cost, not the GPU. The GPU finishes instantly and
[m  waits.

[m  So it's not "weak app vs strong game." It's: [22;1mthe[22m [22;1mGPU[22m [22;1misn't[22m [22;1mthe[22m [22;1mbottleneck[22m [22;1m—[22m [22;1mone[22m [22;1mCPU
[m  [22;1mthread[22m [22;1mdoing[22m [22;1mbookkeeping[22m [22;1mfor[22m [22;1m1400[22m [22;1mUI[22m [22;1mobjects[22m [22;1mis.[22m Your GPU is bored.

[m  [22;1mWhy[22m [22;1m"simple[22m [22;1mwallpaper[22m [22;1mapp"[22m [22;1mis[22m [22;1mmisleading:[22m showing 110 rich cards (image + title + button
[m  + badges + hover states) at once is ~1400 live UI objects. That's a [3mlot[23m for any
[m  retained-mode UI — WPF, Electron, browsers all choke on huge on-screen lists too. That's
[m  literally why virtualization exists (we use it — only on-screen cards are live). At Large
[m  size (~30 cards) you ARE at locked 60. Small just packs 110 on screen.

[m  [22;1mTwo[22m [22;1mhonest[22m [22;1mcontributors:
[m  1. Avalonia's per-object overhead is higher than a hand-tuned engine (general-purpose
[m  toolkit).
[m  2. Our card template is heavier than it needs to be (~13 objects/card; could be ~5).

[m  [22;1mThe[22m [22;1mfix[22m [22;1mthat[22m [22;1mactually[22m [22;1mhelps:[22m make each card cheaper (fewer objects) → the CPU walks fewer
[m  per frame. That's the "flatten the template" option. Cut ~13→~5 objects/card and Small
[m  can approach 60. It's the only real lever, and it's genuinely fixable — the card template
[m  is just doing more than it needs.

