[m[38:2:248:248:242m●[38:2:241:250:140m [22;1;39mWhy one thread:[22m nearly every UI toolkit pins UI state + layout to a single "UI thread" on
[m  purpose — so two things can't mutate the same widget at once (no locks, no races).
[m  Win32, WPF, GTK, Qt, Android, the browser main thread — all the same model. Avalonia [3mdoes
[m  offload GPU submission to a separate render thread; what's stuck on the UI thread is the
[m  [22;1mlayout + scene-diff walk[22m (1400 objects). And layout is hard to parallelize — a parent's
[m  size depends on its children, so it's inherently sequential. So it's standard design, not
[m  a bug.
[m   
[m  [22;1mWould a different library be smarter? Honestly — for [3mthis specific thing[23m, yes:

[m  ┌────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
[m  │        Tool        │              Fit for high-fps image-grid scroll               │
[m  ├────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
[m  │ [22;1mWeb [22m               │ Best. Browser engines have world-class scroll virtualization  │
[m  │ [22;1m(Tauri/Electron + [22m │ + GPU layer compositing, and can run at full refresh (breaks  │
[m  │ [22;1mHTML/CSS)[22m          │ the 60 cap too). A grid of 1000s of images scrolling at       │
[m  │                    │ 144/240 is their home turf.                                   │
[m  ├────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
[m  │ [22;1mFlutter[22m            │ Also excellent (own Skia engine, great list perf,             │
[m  │                    │ high-refresh capable).                                        │
[m  ├────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
[m  │ [22;1mQt/QML[22m             │ Mature, GPU scene-graph, handles big lists well.              │
[m  ├────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
[m  │ [22;1mAvalonia (now)[22m     │ Fine for normal UIs; weaker at huge live on-screen lists, and │
[m  │                    │  X11-capped at 60.                                            │
[m  └────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

[m  So two real wins from switching: (1) escape the 60 cap, (2) much cheaper scrolling.

[m  [22;1mThe catch:[22m it's a [22;1mfull rewrite[22m of a working app in a different language (JS/Dart/C++).
[m  Weeks of work to re-do every feature, for a wallpaper [3mbrowser[23m where Large/Medium already
[m  hit 60. That's a big bet for "Small size scrolls at 60 / get 240."
